==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} ''[[declenson]]'', from {{etyl|frm|en}} ''[[declinaison]]'' (Modern French: ''[[déclinaison]]''), from {{etyl|la|en}} ''[[declinatio]]'' ([[genitive|gen.]] ''declinationis'')

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/dɪˈklɛn.ʃən/}}

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|grammar|lang=en}}: A way of categorizing [[noun]]s, [[pronoun]]s, or [[adjective]]s according to the inflections they receive.
#: ''In Latin, 'amicus' belongs to the second '''declension'''. Most second-declension nouns end in '-i' in the genitive singular and '-um' in the accusative singular.''
# {{context|grammar|lang=en}}: The act of [[decline|declining]] a word; the act of listing the [[inflection]]s of a noun, pronoun or adjective in order.

